      <hedline>
        <hl1>Jerusalem's Future: A Capital of Peace</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Allan J Sobin letter on Karen Armstrong's July 16 article opposes Arab sovereignty in Jerusalem</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Karen Armstrong (Op-Ed, July 16) alludes to the benign nature of Arab control of Jerusalem, but she omits certain historical facts. In 1948, when Jordan's Arab Legion conquered the Old City of Jerusalem, Jews were expelled, synagogues were destroyed and Jews were not allowed to worship at their most holy site, the Western Wall.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Karen Armstrong (Op-Ed, July 16) alludes to the benign nature of Arab control of Jerusalem, but she omits certain historical facts. In 1948, when Jordan's Arab Legion conquered the Old City of Jerusalem, Jews were expelled, synagogues were destroyed and Jews were not allowed to worship at their most holy site, the Western Wall.</p>
        <p>Contrast that with the Israeli conquest of the Old City in 1967. The Arab populace was allowed to remain, mosque attendance was unimpeded, and the Muslims retained control of their holy sites on the Temple Mount. Is it not obvious why Jews should not allow Arab sovereignty in Jerusalem?</p>
        <p>ALLAN J. SOBIN  New York, July 16, 2000</p>
      </block>
